1. Project Overview 

 

1.1 Background 

West Africa is home to over 400 million people, the majority of whom depend on subsistence and smallholder agriculture for their livelihoods and food security. The region produces four principal staple crops — cassava, maize, rice, and sorghum — which together form the dietary foundation of communities across Nigeria, Ghana, Mali, Senegal, and Côte d’Ivoire. 

Scientific consensus and observational data confirm that West Africa is warming at a rate approximately 1.5 times faster than the global average. Changes in temperature, rainfall variability, and the frequency of extreme weather events are directly threatening agricultural productivity, yet a clear, data-driven picture of these impacts has remained largely inaccessible to policymakers, agricultural planners, and the public. 

1.2 Problem Statement 

This project addresses a critical gap: the absence of an accessible, interactive visualization platform that links historical climate trends to measurable changes in staple crop yields across West Africa. Without such a tool: 

Governments cannot target agricultural interventions effectively. 

Researchers lack a consolidated view of cross-country yield divergences. 

Development organisations cannot communicate the urgency of climate adaptation to non-technical stakeholders. 

 

Key Project Fact 

 

Nigeria — the continent’s most populous nation — saw cassava yields collapse from a peak of 12,216 kg/ha in 2010 to just 5,841 kg/ha in 2024, a decline of over 52%. Ghana, meanwhile, nearly doubled its cassava yields over the same period. These diverging trajectories tell a story of policy, climate, and resilience that demands urgent analytical attention. 

 

1.3 Project Goals 

Collect and consolidate 25 years (2000–2024) of FAO crop yield data for 5 West African countries and 4 staple crops into a structured Excel workbook. 

Use Power Query to clean, transform, and model the dataset for analysis. 

Apply Excel-based statistical tools to identify long-term yield trends and anomalies. 

Build an interactive Power BI dashboard enabling dynamic exploration of crop-climate relationships. 

Integrate AI-powered narrative insights to make findings accessible to non-technical audiences. 

Align findings with SDG 2 (Zero Hunger) and SDG 13 (Climate Action) reporting frameworks. 

