3. Solution Explanation 

 

3.1 Solution Architecture 

The solution is built entirely within the Microsoft ecosystem: raw FAO data is ingested and cleaned in Power Query (within Excel), structured into an analytical data model, and then connected to Power BI for interactive visualisation and reporting. The three-layer architecture ensures that every step from raw data to published insight is traceable, reproducible, and auditable. 

 

Architecture Overview 

 

Layer 1 — Raw Data: FAO STAT CSV files (500 rows across 5 countries, 4 crops, 25 years) 

Layer 2 — Transformation: Power Query (M language) for cleaning, shaping, and merging datasets 

Layer 3 — Analysis: Excel workbook with structured tables, pivot tables, trend calculations, and DAX measures 

Layer 4 — Visualisation: Power BI Desktop report connected to the Excel data model, published to Power BI Service 

 

3.2 Data Collection & Preparation 

Raw yield data was downloaded from the FAO STAT portal in CSV format, covering yield data (kg/ha) for the following dimensions: 

 

Dimension 

Values Covered 

Countries 

Nigeria, Ghana, Mali, Senegal, Côte d’Ivoire 

Crops 

Cassava, Maize, Rice, Sorghum 

Time Period 

2000 – 2024 (25 years, 500 data points) 

Format 

CSV files downloaded from FAOSTAT, one file per country 

 

3.3 Power Query Transformation Steps 

All data cleaning and transformation was performed in Power Query Editor within Excel. The following transformation steps were applied: 

Source connection: Connected to the five FAO STAT CSV files using the ‘From Folder’ connector to batch-load all country files simultaneously. 

Column filtering: Removed irrelevant FAO metadata columns (flag descriptions, domain codes, area codes), retaining only Country, Year, Crop, and Yield (kg/ha). 

Data type enforcement: Set Year to Whole Number, Yield to Decimal Number, Country and Crop to Text. 

Null handling: Replaced null yield values using the Fill Down method where sequential years were missing; flagged estimated values with a Boolean ‘IsEstimated’ column. 

Append queries: Combined all five country queries into a single master table using ‘Append Queries as New’. 

Crop name standardisation: Applied a Replace Values step to ensure consistent crop naming across all source files (e.g., ‘Cassava and products’ → ‘Cassava’). 

Year range filter: Applied a row filter to retain only years 2000–2024. 

Load to Excel table: Loaded the final query output to an Excel table named ‘MasterYieldData’ for use as the analysis and Power BI data source. 

3.4 Key Data Findings 

Analysis of 25 years of yield data reveals sharply diverging trajectories across the five countries: 

 

Country / Crop 

Key Trend (2000–2024) 

Ghana — Cassava 

Yield doubled from 12,281 to 25,865 kg/ha (+110%) — strongest performance in the dataset. 

Nigeria — Cassava 

Yield collapsed from 12,216 kg/ha (2010) to 5,841 kg/ha (2024) — a 52% decline. 

Senegal — Cassava 

Yield tripled from 4,888 to 14,803 kg/ha, driven by PNAR investment and irrigation. 

Côte d’Ivoire — Cassava 

Sustained 32% decline from 7,743 (2000) to 5,261 (2021), partially recovered by 2024. 

Senegal — Rice 

Yields grew from 2,345 to 3,851 kg/ha, supported by irrigated paddy expansion. 

All Countries — Sorghum 

High year-to-year volatility — a clear signal of rainfall sensitivity. 

All Countries — Maize 

Modest gains (+25% average), but yields remain below regional potential. 

 

