Why Microsoft 365? 

 

The Microsoft Excel + Power Query + Power BI stack was deliberately chosen over specialist data science tools because it is already embedded in the working environments of most government ministries, development agencies, and academic institutions across West Africa. This means that stakeholders can not only consume the outputs but also open, verify, and extend the underlying analysis themselves — a critical requirement for long-term institutional uptake. 

 

5. AI Component Explanation 

 

5.1 Overview 

Although the core analysis was conducted using Microsoft Excel, Power Query, and Power BI, artificial intelligence was integrated at two key stages: during data preparation and validation, and within the Power BI dashboard as a plain-language insight generation layer. The AI component bridges the gap between statistical outputs and human-readable interpretation. 

5.2 Claude AI (Anthropic) — Insight Generation 

Claude AI was used to generate narrative interpretations of the yield trend data throughout this project. Specifically, Claude was provided with structured data slices from the Excel master table and asked to produce plain-language summaries that could be embedded in the Power BI ‘Insight’ text box and in stakeholder reports. 

 

Example AI-Generated Insight 

 

“Ghana demonstrates that with sustained investment in improved planting material, irrigation infrastructure, and market access programmes, cassava yields can double within two decades — even as regional temperatures rise. Nigeria’s trajectory, however, illustrates what happens when these enablers are withdrawn: yields collapse to levels lower than the year 2000 baseline, creating acute food insecurity for the largest population on the continent.” 

 

— Claude AI pattern analysis across 5 countries × 4 crops × 25 years 

 

Claude AI was used during the project for the following specific tasks: 

Data review: Claude was provided with the raw FAO dataset to identify inconsistencies, flag outlier years, and highlight country-crop combinations requiring further investigation before Power Query cleaning began. 

Trend narration: After pivot table outputs were produced in Excel, Claude generated plain-language descriptions of each country’s yield trend for use in the final report and Power BI Insight Panel. 

Anomaly contextualisation: Claude was asked to suggest probable explanations for flagged anomalies (e.g., Nigeria 2012–2013 yield collapse, Senegal 2005 cassava spike) drawing on general knowledge of regional agricultural policy and climate events. 

Report drafting: Claude assisted in drafting sections of this project documentation and the accompanying presentation, based on structured prompts containing the analysed data. 

5.3 Power BI AI Visuals 

Power BI’s built-in AI features were also utilised within the dashboard: 

Smart Narrative Visual: Power BI’s Smart Narrative feature was enabled on the Overview page, automatically generating a text summary of the currently selected data view in real time as users adjust slicers. 

Q&A Visual: A Q&A text field was added to the Country Deep Dive page, allowing users to type natural language questions (e.g., ‘What was Ghana’s average cassava yield between 2010 and 2020?’) and receive instant visual answers. 

Anomaly Detection (Preview Feature): Power BI’s built-in anomaly detection was applied to the cassava and maize trend line charts, automatically highlighting statistically unusual data points with explanatory tooltips. 

Key Influencers Visual: Applied to the dataset to surface which country and crop combinations were most strongly associated with above-average and below-average yield performance. 

5.4 Excel AI Assistance 

Within Excel itself, AI-assisted features were used to accelerate analysis: 

Copilot in Excel (where available): Used to generate initial pivot table configurations and suggest conditional formatting rules based on natural language prompts. 

Ideas / Analyze Data feature: Excel’s built-in ‘Analyze Data’ pane was used in the exploratory phase to surface automatically detected trends, outliers, and distribution patterns in the MasterYieldData table. 

Formula suggestions: Excel’s AI-powered formula suggestions assisted in constructing FORECAST.ETS and AVERAGEIFS formulas for the trend projection sheet. 

