6.3 Challenges Encountered 

Challenge 1: Inconsistent FAO CSV File Structures 

The FAO STAT CSV files downloaded for different countries were not identically structured — some included additional metadata columns, some used different crop name conventions, and some had varying column header names across download batches. 

Resolution: The Power Query ‘From Folder’ transformation was set to select only named columns (rather than by position), and a Replace Values step was added to standardise all crop name variants. A column selection step was placed after the Append Queries step to enforce a consistent final schema. 

Challenge 2: Excel File Size Growth 

As the project progressed, the Excel workbook grew significantly as pivot caches, chart data, and multiple query outputs accumulated. At one point the file exceeded 45MB, causing slow load times and occasional crashes during pivot table refresh. 

Resolution: Pivot table caches were disabled for non-essential pivots (‘Save source data with file’ unchecked). Charts were moved to separate chart sheets. Power Query ‘Load to Data Model only’ was used for secondary summary queries that did not need to appear as worksheet tables, reducing the overall file size to under 12MB. 

Challenge 3: Power BI DAX Measure Complexity for YoY Calculations 

Calculating year-over-year yield change in DAX required careful handling of the date dimension, because the dataset is annual (not daily), and the standard DATEADD time intelligence functions required a properly marked Date table. 

Resolution: A separate Date dimension table was created in Power Query (List.Numbers generating a sequence from 2000 to 2024), marked as the Date Table in Power BI, and linked to the MasterYieldData Year column. This enabled standard DAX time intelligence functions to work correctly for the YoY change measure. 

Challenge 4: Power BI Smart Narrative Producing Generic Text 

Power BI’s Smart Narrative visual, while useful, initially produced overly generic summaries (“Yield values range from X to Y”) that did not capture the analytical story the team needed to communicate. 

Resolution: Smart Narrative was retained as a supplementary feature but the primary insight text in the dashboard was replaced with a static text visual populated with Claude AI-generated narrative. For each key finding (e.g., Ghana vs. Nigeria cassava comparison), a dedicated Claude-generated insight was formatted and embedded as a fixed text box, updated manually when the slicer selection changes to a new country-crop focus. 

Challenge 5: Sharing Power BI Reports Without Pro Licences 

Several target stakeholders, particularly within government ministries, did not have Power BI Pro licences, which are required to view reports published to Power BI Service workspaces. 

Resolution: The report was also exported as a static PDF for email distribution, and the Power BI file (.pbix) was shared directly for stakeholders with Power BI Desktop (free). For the wider public-facing version, Power BI’s ‘Publish to Web’ feature was used to generate an embeddable iFrame link accessible in any browser without authentication. 

6.4 Lessons Learned 

Design the Power Query pipeline first: Every hour spent carefully structuring the transformation steps in Power Query saves three hours of manual Excel fixes downstream. Investing in a clean, well-documented query pipeline before building any analysis or visuals was the single best decision of the project. 

Name everything: Named tables in Excel, named queries in Power Query, and named measures in Power BI make the project navigable for any team member and dramatically simplify troubleshooting. Unnamed ranges and queries become a maintenance burden very quickly. 

Power BI and Excel are stronger together: The combination of Excel’s familiarity and flexibility for analysis with Power BI’s visualisation and sharing capabilities is more powerful than either tool alone. Keeping Excel as the single source of truth and Power BI as the presentation layer worked well. 

AI narration fills the last mile: The hardest part of data communication is translating a chart into a decision. Claude AI’s narrative generation addressed this gap, producing stakeholder-ready language from structured data in seconds. 

The Ghana-Nigeria contrast is the project’s strongest narrative: Two neighbouring countries with similar starting yields producing radically different trajectories provides both analytical depth and clear policy implications. Centering the Power BI report on this comparison significantly improved stakeholder engagement. 

Licence constraints are a real barrier: The Power BI Pro licensing issue was not anticipated and caused delays in stakeholder sharing. Future projects should audit the licence landscape of target users before choosing a distribution strategy. 

 

